        <substitution method="pen" type="deletion" copyText="'' Out of the shot and danger of desire:" amendedText=""/>
 
        <substitution method="pen" type="deletion" copyText="
            '' Virtue if self seapes not caluminious strokes |
            '' The canker galls the infant of the Spring |
            '' Too oft before their buttons bedifoles’d |
            '' And in the morn and liquid dew of youth |
            '' Cantagious blastments are most imminent |
            '' Be wary then best safety lies in fear, |
            '' Youth to it self rebells though none elfe near."
           amendedText=""/>
           
        <substitution method="pen" type="deletion" copyText="" amendedText="“And reaks not his own reed, "/>
        
        <substitution method="pen" type="deletion" copyText="'' A double blessing is a double grace, | '' Occasion smiles upon a second leave," amendedText=""/>"/>
        
        <substitution method="pen" type="deletion" copyText="
            '' There, my blessing with thee, |
            '' And these few precepts in thy memory |
            '' Look thou character: Give thy thoughts no tongue, |
            '' Nor any unproportion’d thought act: |
            '' Be thou familiar, but by no means: vulgar: |
            '' Those friends thou hast and their adoption tried, |
            '' Grapple them unto thy palm with entertainment |
            '' Of each new hatch’t unfledge’d courage: beware |
            '' Of entrance to a quarrel, but being in, |
            '' Bear’t that th’ oppose may beware of thee: |
            '' Give every man thy ear, but few thy voice; |
            '' Take each mans censure, but reserve thy judgement: |
            '' Costly thy habit as thy purse can buy, |
            '' But not exprest in fancy; rich, not gaudy; |
            '' For the apparel oft proclaims the man, |
            '' And they in France of the Best rank and station, |
            '' Are of the most select and generous, chief in that: |
            '' Neither a borrower nor a lender boy, |
            '' For love oft loses both it self and friend, |
            '' And borrowing dulls the edge of husbandry."
            amendedText=""/>
                
